{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559484/1949051201/0192.xml":{"full_text":"OLD FORT SCHOOL WINS\n(Continued from first page)\nthird place, Rosemary Dover, Pleas\nant Garden school. Third class girls\n50 yard relay: first place, Joyce\nCiisson, North Cove school, Jose\nphine Shuford, Pleasant Garden\nschool, Nancy Morgan, Old Fort\nschool. Third class boys 50 yard\nd?sh; first place Wayne Brooks,\nPleasant Gardens School; second\nplace, Harold Plemmons, Old Fort\nschool; third place, Dackie Swof\nford, North Cove school. Third class\nboys 50 yard relay: first place,\nTommie Henley, Pleasant Garden\nschool; second place, Ralph D4vis,\nOld Fort school; third place, Guy\nBlankenship, North Cove school.\nThird class girls block race: first\nplace, Jean Jenkins, Nebo school;\nsecond place, Willie Morgan, Sugar\nHill school; third place, Peggy Bur\ngin, Pleasant Gardens school. Block\nrace girls second class: first place,\nDarlene. Jenkins, Nebo School; se\ncond place, three ties, Jean Litel\nlier, North Cove school; Alma Law\ning, Sugar Hill school; Betty Jane\nByrd, Pleasant Gardens school. Third\nclass boys three legged race: first\nplace Jimmy Wright, North Cove\nschool; second place, Lester Hen\nsley and Lee Glenn Boyd and M'c\nMahan, Pleasant Gardens school;\nMahan, Pleasant Garden school;\nKenneth Carver and Frank Banks,\nOld Fort school. Third place boys\nsack race: first place, J. C. Allison,\nOld Fort school; second place, Boy\nce Burnette, North Cove school.\nSecond class girls 50 yard dash:\nfirst place, Christine Ledford, Old\nFort school; second place, Betty\nMcNeil, Pleasant Garden school;\nthird place, Lilla B Jenkins, Nebo\nschool. Second class girls 100 yard\ndash: first place Joyce Harris, Old\nFort school; second place, Barbara\nAnn Wiseman, Pleasant Garden\nschool. Second class girls 50 yard\nrelay: first place, Patsy Mclntire\nOld Fort school; second place, Fran\nces Silver, Pleasant Garden school;\nthird place, Velma Ruth Hughes,\nNorth Cove. Second class boys 50\nyard dash: first place, Jerry McKin\nney, North Cove school; second\nplace, Donald Lackey, Old Fort\nschool; third place, Jimmy Fox, Ne\nbo school. Second class boys 100\nyard dash: first place, Ernest Ogle,\nNorth Cove school; second place,\nHoward Morgan, Nebo school; third\nplace, Carl Farmer, Old Fort. Se-'\ncond class boys 50 yard relay: first\nplace, Dean Wright, North Cove\nschool; second place, Paul Bi-ooks,\nPleasant Garden school; third place,\nDonald Lyda, Old Fort.\nFirst class girls 50 yard dash: first\nplace, Zelda Swofford, North Cove\nschool; second place, Minnie Elkine,\nPleasant Garden school; third place,\nRuby Shell, Glenwood school. First\nclass girls 100 yard dash: first place,\nBetty Williams, North Cove school;\nsecond place, Hazel Walker, Old\nFort; third place, Ellen McPeters,\nPleasant Garden. First class girls\n50 yard relay: first place, Lasell\nLight, Old Fort school; second place,\nRuth Washburn, North Cove; third\nplace, Beulah Wilson, Pleasant Gar\ndens. First place girls ^basketball\nthrow for distance: first place, An\nnie Ray (70.11 ft.) Glenwood\nschool; second place, Ruth Buff\n(64 ft.) Nebo school; Betty Bur\nnette (58.2V2 ft.) Pleasant Garden\nschool.\nFirst class boys 100 yard dash:\nfirst place, William Bradley, Old\nFort; second place, Allen Cling,\nNorth Cove; third place, Leo Wat\nson, Nebo school. First place, Tho\nmas Hogan, North Cove; third place,\nVernie McCall, Pleasant Garden\nschool. First class boys 220 yard\ndash: first place, Willard Huskins,\nNorth Cove school; second place,\nEugene Bradley, Old Fort school;\nEdward Poteat, Glenwood school.\nFirst class boys Running High\n\u2022Jump: first place, Clyde Silver, Old\nFort school; second place, Hunter\nBallew, Nebo school; third place,\nJoe English, North Cove school.\nSecond class boys Running High\nJump: first place, Jimmie Vess, Old\nFort school; second place, Harold j\nBoyd, North Cove school, third i\nplace, Bill Hensley, Pleasant Gar-;\ndens school.\nFirst class boys Running Broad\nJump: first place, Jimmie Harris\n(17 ft.) Old Fort school; second\nplace, .Wayne Morris (16 ft, 11%\nin.) Glenwood school; third place,\nDonald Wells (16 ft. 1% ins.) Nebo\nschool.\nSecond class boys Pull Up: first\nplace, Gilmer Hennessee (22 times)\nNorth Cove school; second place,\nBilly Lawing (20 times) Old Fort;\nthird place, Kit Hicks (15 times)\nNebo school.\nSecond class boys Running Broad\nJump: first place, Theodore John\nson, (14 ft. 4^4 ins.) Old Fort\nschool; second place, Johnnie Byrd\n(14 ft. *4 in.) Pleasant Garden\nschool; third place, Frank Queen\n(13 ft. 2Ys in.) Nebo school.\nPLEASANT GARDENS SCHOOL\n(Continued from first page)\nlis, George Williams, Jackie Byrd,\nDoris Hensley, Glenda Mooney,\nJune Shuford, Mary Alice Godfrey,\nRose Marie Dover, Barbara Shu\nford, Jeanette Jimeson, Rita Lee\nDover, Pauline Suttles, Oleta Mc\nMahan, Edward Fulghum, Billie Ann\nVess, Nancy Finley, James Free\nman, Joan Rabb.\nCarolyn Withrow, Elaine Shu\nford, Eunice Burnette, Nell Bur\nnette, Margaret Hensley, Mary\nAlice Godfrey, Carolyn Blackwell,\nRuby Fox.\nFinal exercises will be held at 8\np. m., May 20. The program fol\nlows:\nProcessional, Seniors.\nPresident of Class of '49\u2014Master\nof Ceremonies, Carl McKinney, Jr.\nWelcome, My America, Julia Ann\nnemming.\nLiberty, James Buckner.\nUnity, Alta Jo Ellis.\nDemocracy, Harold Pittman.\nSecurity, Carrie Burnette.\nMusic, Glee Club: Blue Danube\nWaltz, Strauss; My Lindy Lou,\nStrickland.\nOur Challenge, Kathleen Cox Bur\nnette.\nOur Fathers, Macon Ann Har\nshaw.\nPresentation of Diplomas and\nMedals, Mr. Wiggins.\nDiploma of Acceptance Speech,\nCarl McKinney, Jr.\nRecessional, Seniors.\nHonor students of the class this\nyear are: Macon Ann Harshaw, val\nedictorian, with an average of 97.57,\nand Ann Wright Queen averaging\n95.22.\nThe graduating class is composed\nof: Carrie Burnette, Marjorie Cor\ndell, Kathleen Cox Burnette, Marie\nElliott, Alta Jo Ellis, Julia Ann\nFleming, Rettie June Gardner, Ma\ncon Ann Harshaw, Gretchen Heers,\nInez Morgan, Doris Vess, Queenia\nWilliams, Ann Wright Queen.\nJames Buckner, Bobby Comer, j\nRalph Justice, Billy McDaniels, Carl I\nMcKinney, Jr., D. C. McKinney,\nHarold Pittman, Troy Proctor, Jim-1\nmy Setzer, Durward Walker.\nSHELBY FARMERS\n(Continued from flrst page)\nslide thru the game until the nine\nnnings had been completed.\nRookie Pitcher Fox attempted to\nstop the Farmers after they had\nlopped on his fast ball in the first'\nnning for a home run and a two\nDoint lead. He was forced to give\nvay to Presnell in the sixth frame,\n.vhen the Farmers staged a rally\n.vhich netted them six runs. Pres\nlell was able to stem the tide for\n;he remainder of the game. Marion\n;ommitted three errors, which was j\nto be expected due to weather con- j\nditions, but such errors did not help\nthe Marauder cause.\nGene Goforth, working for Shel\nby, was touched for nine hits, but\nrie was able to scatter them to the\njxtent that no damage was done.\nRay Yow homered for the locals\nsut the game had already been lost.\nBrooks and Beam claimed extra\n>ase knocks with a triple each,\n)ut their effort failed to change the\nesult. Charlie Hutchins and Walter\nAlexander led the hitting for Shel\niy, each with three for five.\nThe line score was:\nMarion ___ 000 002 101\u2014 3 9 3\nShelby 200 200 60x\u201410 13 2\nBatteries: Fox, Pressnell (7) to\nBonetti; Goforth to Borick.\nDoubles: Alexander, Brown and\nMiller; triples: Beam and Brooks;\nhome-runs: Yow and Hutchins.\nLEAGUE STANDINGS\nMARAUDERS WIN\nThe Marion Marauders bounced)\nback in the win column in two gam\nes played away from home last Sat\nurday and Sunday.\nIn the first game played in Lenoir\nSaturday night Nat Yablon held the\nRed Sox to five hits in a ten in\nning affair, while his team mates\nracked up three runs which were\nsufficient to bring home a three to\ntwo victory. Lenoir is in the top\nflight position and this win was es\npecially gratifying to Johnny Lan\nning, top boss of the fighting Marion\nM'arauders.\nOn Sunday the Marauders took a\nbus over to Hendersonville and a\ngame away from Rube Wilson's\nHendersonville Skylarks to the tune\nof three to one.\nJohnny Lanning, manager of Ma\nrion's offering of the Western Car\nolina league assigned himself to the\nmound for the locals. For seven\nstraight innings he tossed matchless\nball and set down the first eighteen\nmen to face him without so much\nas a single trip to first. Lanning, a\nformer big leaguer, his first assign\nment without difficulty and allow\ned only two hits during the entire\ngame. He received excellent support\nfrom his entire squad. Tom Cumby\ncame through with a home run to\nstart the Marauder offense. The\nscore was tied in the seventh, but\nthe Marionites were able to bring\nin two more runs before the end of\nNewton\nR. C. Owls\nMarion\nLenoir\nLincolnton\nHendersonville\nMorganton\nShelby __\nW L Pet\n7 2 778\n7 4 636 I\n6 6 500 I\n4 4 500\n4 4 500\n5 6 455\n3 5 375\n2 7 222\nthe game to claim the victory.\nBatteries for Marion: Lanning to\nBonnetti; for the Skylarks, Eddy to\nHunt.\nBASEBALL\nSCHEDULE\nThursday, May 12: Morganton at\nMarion.\nFriday, May 13: Marion at Lin\ncolnton.\nSaturday, May 14: Lincolnton at\nMarion.\nMonday, May 16: Marion at New\nton.\nTuesday: May 17: Newton at Ma\nrion.\nWednesday, May 18: Marion at\nHendersonville.\nAll the home games will be played\non the high school athletic field at\n8:00 o'clock.\nROBERT ELLIS\n(Gontinued from first page)\nto imformation. He died shortly af\nterward in a Huron hospital without\nregaining consciousness. He was\nalone at the time of the accident.\nEllis, who served four years in\nthe Army during World War II, at\ntended Mars Hill College and was\ngraduated last June from the School j\nof Engineering of North Carolina\nState College. He was married in j\nNovember to the former Miss Eve-!\nlyn Melluch of Cleveland. j\nSurviving are the mother who re- J\nsides in Marion; the widow, Mrs. j\nEvelyn Melluch Ellis of Cleveland\nthree sisters, Mrs. Robert Gibson\nand Miss Dottie Sue Ellis of Marion j\nand Miss Jean Ellis of Spartanburg,;\nS. C., and two brothers, Hugh Ed\nward Ellis, serving with the Army\nat Washington, D. C,f and Troy El\nlis of Marion.\nOLD FORT COMMENCEMENT\n(Continued from first page\nthe Baccalaureate sermon. After\nwards a quartette will render a vo\ncal selection. Rev. F. M. Wilson will\npronounce the benediction and the\nservice will close with a recession\nal. i\nMarshalls this year arer Doris\nDavis, Lucille Grindstaff, Elsie\nJohnson, Clara Kelly, Doris Oliver\nand Mabel Tabor.\nThe following program wiTf be\npresented:\nProcessional, Pomp and Circum\nstances, Elgar.\nInvocation, Rev. N. S. O'gburn.\nChorus, Silent Now The Drowsy\nBird. J. Offenbach.\nSalutatory, Louise Bailey.\nPresentation of Speaker, Harry\nSwofford.\nLiterary Address, Blanton's B*\u00absi-j\nness College, Dr. Victor L. Hovis.\nChorus, An Irish Love Song, Ka-i\ntberine Hinkson.\nPresentation of Diplomas, Mr. N. j\nF. Steppe, Superintendent Mc-!\nDowell county schools.\nPresentation of Awards, Harry j\nSwofford.\nSolo, Trees, Patsy Burgin.\nMARION BAND CONCERT\n(Continued from page one)\ntral), Greensboro, Lenoir, and Con\ncord as the top school concert band's\nin the state. A first class concert is\npredicted.\nAll of the music on the program\nis not the heavy type. The program\nis diversified enough to appeal to\nthe average concert-goer. Select;pns\nL-ange from Hoagy CarmichaeFs\n\"Star Dust\" to the first movement\nof Fauchet's \"Symphony in B Flat\",\nan original symphony composition\nfor band.\nConcert time has been set Back\nto 8:15 for this concert to avoid\nconflict with the regular Wednes\nday night church services.\nMcdowell census\n(Continued from first page)'\nand was passed by the 80th (Con\ngress. Olham pointed out that the\nfilling of the individual report forms\nfor this Business Census will not re\nquire more than two minutes of\na business man's time if he wilT give\nth information to Mr. Lonon the\nfirst time he calls on him. Tfte 1948\nBusiness Census will cover all' whole\nsale, retail and service trad'e estab\nlishments.\nOldham pointed out further that\nall of the information supplied by\nthe business men will' be strictly\nconfidential and that it cannot be\nused for purposes of taxation, inves\ntigation or regulation..\nWBRM BROADCAST\n(Continued from first page)\ntype program presented. Daytime\nreception was reported loud and\nclear within a radius of 50 to 60\nmiles of Marion. The most distant\ndaytime reception was reported\nfrom Cincinnati, Ohio last Monday\nafternoon.\nFormal Dedication\nFormal dedication of the local\nstation will be made Sunday, Maj\n29, in the high school auditorium\nwith Governor Kerr Scott as speak\ner. Details of the dedication are in\ncomplete.\nNo Wonder More and More Food\nShoppers Are Swinging to\nHOLLER'S\nCompare Prices\nTEA, Lipton's\ny4 ib. __\n29c\nJEWEL SHORTENING\n4 lbs only\n75c\nCRISCO and SNOWDRIFT\n3 lbs\n89c\nWESSON OIL\npint\n29c\nGULF SPRAY\npint\n19c\nJ F G COFFEE j|\\\n1 lb. 4tfc\nSUGAR\n10 lbs.\nRINSO\nlarge box\n89c\n29c\nSOAPr Large' Ivory and: Swan\n2 for\n29c\nLUX SOAP\n2 large\n19c\nTCWELS, Scotts\n2 rolls\n29c\nTISSUE PAPER;\n4 roils\n25c\nROLL MIX Pillsbury and Ditffs\npackage\nBABY FOOD, Gerbers\n3* for\n24c\n27c\nCARNATION MILK\ntall, 2 for\n25c\nDESSERT MIX, Lipton's, Frostee\n2 pkgs.\nSALMON,\ntall can\n25c\n45c\nImm\n4'\"\"\ny: (Absolutely\n'^Spure and HJncooked\nJS.-.;\nWORTH WAITING FOR\nPINT, 45c\nQUALITY MEATS\n14c rNERS 39c\nFAT BACK, thick 1 WEINERS\nlb.\nPORK SAUSAGE, pure 3I0C cure<*> sliced 05C\nFRYERS, Fresh, table dressed 5dC\nPORK ROAST y|g$ FRYERS, Fresh, table dressed\nlb. L\nWholesome\nVegetable\nMargarine\n29c\nBLUE PLATE\nPEANUT\nBUTTER\nMade from No. 1\nPeanuts\nPINT\n39c\nBlue Plate\nMayonnaise\nMad& by the Wesson\nOil Company\nPint Jar\n45c\nMore 